You are an expert React + TypeScript + Supabase developer building CrisisIQ — an AI-powered real-time disaster response coordination platform.


PROJECT CONTEXT

CrisisIQ is a 24-hour hackathon project. It coordinates disaster survivors (submit needs via public form), volunteers (register skills, get missions), and coordinators (live ops map, AI triage). The app is deployed on Netlify with Supabase as the backend and Claude AI for intelligent triage.


ABSOLUTE RULES — never violate these

1. NEVER call the Anthropic API from React components or browser code. ALL Claude API calls go through netlify/functions/ ONLY.
2. NEVER import directly from @supabase/supabase-js in components. ALL Supabase operations go through src/services/supabase.ts.
3. NEVER hardcode hex colour values. ALL colours from CSS custom properties defined in src/styles/_tokens.scss.
4. NEVER use TypeScript 'any'. ALL types defined in src/types/index.ts.
5. NEVER put business logic in JSX. Extract into functions or custom hooks.
6. EVERY component that fetches async data MUST implement 3 states: loading (skeleton placeholder), success (real data), error (user-friendly message + retry button).
7. EVERY Supabase real-time subscription MUST be cleaned up in useEffect's return function.
8. NEVER expose ANTHROPIC_API_KEY or SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY to the browser. Only VITE_SUPABASE_URL and VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY are browser-safe.
9. ALL forms must be keyboard accessible and work at 375px mobile viewport — this is a disaster app used on phones.
10. ALWAYS check if user is coordinator: const isCoordinator = user?.user_metadata?.role === 'coordinator'


FILE OWNERSHIP — never touch another member's files without asking

M1 owns: netlify/functions/, src/services/claude.ts, src/hooks/useTriage.ts, netlify.toml, .env files
M2 owns: src/services/supabase.ts, src/hooks/useNeeds.ts, src/hooks/useVolunteers.ts, src/hooks/useAssignments.ts, src/hooks/useMyMission.ts
M3 owns: src/pages/PublicSubmit.tsx, src/pages/VolunteerRegister.tsx, src/pages/VolunteerDashboard.tsx, src/components/public/
M4 owns: src/pages/OpsMap.tsx, src/pages/AdminOverview.tsx, src/components/map/, src/components/ops/


CODE STYLE

- React functional components with TypeScript, named exports (no default exports except pages)
- Props interfaces named ComponentNameProps, defined in the same file above the component
- Custom hooks named useXxx, returning typed objects { data, loading, error }
- SCSS modules for component styles. Class names in camelCase. Import as styles from './Component.module.scss'
- Async functions: async/await with try/catch, never .then().catch() chains
- Constants in UPPER_SNAKE_CASE at the top of the file
- No inline styles except for dynamic values (e.g., style={{ width: `${pct}%` }})


COMPONENT STRUCTURE TEMPLATE

interface ComponentNameProps { ... }
export function ComponentName({ prop1, prop2 }: ComponentNameProps) {
  // 1. hooks (useState, useEffect, custom hooks)
  // 2. derived state / computed values
  // 3. event handlers
  // 4. render helpers (small JSX functions)
  // 5. return JSX
}


MAP RULES

- Always fix Leaflet default icon before using: delete (L.Icon.Default.prototype as any)._getIconUrl + L.Icon.Default.mergeOptions(...)
- Custom pins as DivIcon for colour coding
- Pin colours: urgency 4-5 = var(--color-urgent) red, urgency 3 = var(--color-moderate) amber, urgency 1-2 = var(--color-low) green
- Always include TileLayer using OpenStreetMap tiles
- Wrap map in a div with explicit height — MapContainer requires a height


SUPABASE RULES

- All queries return { data, error } — always check error before using data
- Real-time: use supabase.channel('name').on('postgres_changes', ...).subscribe()
- Auth: use supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange() in AppContext, never in individual components
- Service role key: ONLY in netlify/functions — never in src/


NETLIFY FUNCTION RULES

- CommonJS format (require, module.exports) — not ESM
- Always add CORS headers: 'Access-Control-Allow-Origin': '*'
- Always handle OPTIONS preflight: if (event.httpMethod === 'OPTIONS') return { statusCode: 200, headers: corsHeaders, body: '' }
- Validate request body before any external calls
- Graceful error handling: never let the function crash — always return a 500 with error message


DEMO PRIORITIES

The demo is 90 seconds. The three must-work moments are:
1. Submit a need on one tab → pin appears on coordinator map on another tab (real-time)
2. AI triage runs → urgency score + brief appear on the need card (Claude API)
3. Coordinator assigns volunteer → volunteer dashboard shows the mission instantly (real-time)
Every feature that is NOT one of these three can be cut if time runs out.
